Hi @noggie108!
Wow, British have 31 days in February?!  Shows how far behind us yanks are... <img title=":_tuzki_teehee:" src="https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/136959/13203716/665ac5c2-d883-11e5-87ef-bbb0be4e1d81.gif"> 

Anyway, you'll need a custom parser since a date with dashes (`-`) won't parse in Firefox ([demo](http://jsfiddle.net/856bzzeL/970/))

```js
$(function() {

  $.tablesorter.addParser({
    // set a unique id
    id: 'special-date',
    is: function() {
      return false;
    },
    format: function(str) {
      // replace the dash in the date with a space
      var date = new Date(str.replace(/-/g, ' '));
      return date instanceof Date && isFinite(date) ? date.getTime() : str;
    },
    // set type, either numeric or text
    type: 'numeric'
  });

  $('table').tablesorter({
    debug: true,
    theme: 'blue',
    widgets: ['zebra']
  });

});
```

Hi @DaveGahan!

I think the issue might be that tablesorter and the pager need to be initialized outside of that ajax function, that is if that code gets executed more than once.

So do something like this:

```js
var $table = $('#ecritures')
  .tablesorter({ /* options */ })
  .tablesorterPager({ /* options */ }),

  config = $table.data('tablesorter');

function getRows(url, urldata) {
  $.get(
    url,
    urldata,
    function(data) {
      var row = '';
      // process data
      $.tablesorter.addRows( config, row, true );
    }
}
```

Oh!

It looks like the table is empty. Please make sure that your HTML is valid and contains one `<thead>` and one `<tbody>`.

It also looks like you're using the original tablesorter - v2.0.5b. If you want to keep using that version then use the `headers` option:

```js
$('table').tablesorter({
  theme: 'blue',
  headers: {
    0: { sorter: 'grades' }, // use zero-based column index
    1: { sorter: 'grades' }
  }
});
```

