With newer FontAwesome versions the above mixin does need a little help. I've modified it below just to make it easier for anyone who may need to do this.

@mixin icon($name) {
  &:before {
    font-family: FontAwesome;
    font-weight: normal;
    font-style: normal;
    display: inline-block;
    text-decoration: inherit;
    margin-right: 0.4em;
  }

  @extend .fa-#{$name};
}

FYI, i just ran into this issue as well, what i did was reference the svg tag in the class, the transition won't on the <i> tag, it needs to affect the child <svg> tag.

`<i class="fa-thumbtack oc-thumbtack-up">`

`.oc-thumbtack-up svg {
    animation: oc-thumbtack-up-kf 200ms ease-out;
    animation-fill-mode: forwards;
    transform-origin: center;
}

@keyframes oc-thumbtack-up-kf {
    0% {
        transform: rotate(0deg);
    }
    100% {
        transform: rotate(90deg);
    }
}

.oc-thumbtack-down svg {
    animation: oc-thumbtack-down-kf 200ms ease-in;
    animation-fill-mode: forwards;
    transform-origin: center;
}

@keyframes oc-thumbtack-down-kf {
    0% {
        transform: rotate(90deg);
    }
    100% {
        transform: rotate(0deg);
    }
}
`

There is an issue in `rotate-flip.[scss/less]` where the MSIE fixes are all declared as separate variables. The only solution I've got is to have each option extend a base selector with that property, however then you are left with a junk property, example below:

```css
.ie-rotation-fix {
  filter: none;
}
```

**SASS extend**
```scss
@for $i from 0 through 359 {
  @if $i == 0 or $i % $fa-rotation-increment == 0 {
    $rotation-selector: #{$fa-css-prefix}-rotate-#{$i};
    // check if this item needs some ie love
    @if $i == 0 or $i % 90 == 0 {
      .#{$rotation-selector} {
        @extend .ie-rotation-fix;
      }
    }
  }
}
```

**LessCSS extend**
```less
:root  {
  .calculateIEFixes(@i) when (@i >= 0) {
    // iterate
    .calculateIEFixes((@i - 1));
      @z: ~"@{wi-css-prefix}-rotate-@{i}";
      .@{z} when (mod(@i, 90) = 0) {
        &:extend(.ie-rotation-fix);
      }
   }
  .calculateIEFixes(359);
}
```

Both options result in
```css
.ie-rotation-fix, .fa-rotate-0, .fa-rotate-90, .fa-rotate-180, .fa-rotate-270 {
  filter: none;
}
```

This is a bit ugly, especially with the erroneous class; however it seems preferable to the alternative of duplicated declarations.

